Introduction¶

With a large dataset of 189 files, I will be analyzing the Net Sales of the coffee shop I work at. I will also be using Facebook's decomposable time-series model to perform forecasting, and to evaluate trends. Since the data I have has strong seasonality due to the shop following the school-year, this method of forecasting will be very precise.

We begin with importing the necessary libraries and proceed to data cleaning. (Feel free to skip to the "Time to Plot!" section)

cleaned_date = []

def dateCleaner(arr):
    for item in arr:
        rawDate = item.split("_")[1].split("-")[0]
        year = rawDate[0:4]
        month = rawDate[4:6]
        day = rawDate[-2:]
        
        finalDate = month + "-" + day + "-" + year
        cleaned_date.append(finalDate)
        
dateCleaner(file_arr)

Data Merging¶

Merging all CSV files into one, to be able to compile easily.

In [10]:
def df_merger(main_df):
    
    frames = [main_df]
    
    #read in the files one by one and clean them up
    for i in range(0, len(file_arr)):
        df = pd.read_csv(file_arr[i])
        df['Date'] = cleaned_date[i]
        frames.append(df)
        
    final = pd.concat(frames)
    
    return final

df = df_merger(final)

Forecasting¶

We begin out forecast using Facebook's Prophet library.

In [15]:
from fbprophet import Prophet

prophet_df = grouped_df[['Date', 'Net Sales']]
prophet_df.columns = ['ds', 'y']

m = Prophet()
m.fit(prophet_df)

Interpretation¶

The blue background behind the lines is an 80% confidence interval. Once the black dots end, that is when the prediction begins. Visually, it seems we have a downward trend of Net Sales for this particular coffee shop.

Below, we analyze specifics.

In [18]:
fig2 = m.plot_components(forecast)

Figure 1 is a trendline. It seems from the time we begin to our forecast of 2 years, we are on a relatively strong downward trend.

Figure 2 shows an average behavior model for Net Sales through a typical year. It is unsurprising that September-October is our strong point. This is likely due to the weather change fom warm to cooler, as well as the beginning of midterms.

Conclusion¶

Based on our analysis, this particular coffee shop is on a downward trend for Net Sales. This must be due to some outside source. Could it be the quality of the coffee? Could it be a decline in attendance? More people not drinking coffee? A Financial burden? Are more people making coffee at home?

There are many possibilities for this decline, and to determine these would be a task left to surveying. I would be interested to learn exactly what the cause is.
